      <p>Hi Everyone! </p>
      <p>
I am Yash Vardhan Raizada, currently a Final Year Undergraduate in the Department of Civil Engineering at IIT Kanpur. In the upcoming summers, after graduating, I will be joining Microsoft as a full-time employee in the role of Software Engineer.
       
      </p> 

      <p>My Journey @ IITK: A brief background</p>

      <p>I would like to share my background in brief about how things were for me in my initial years and how things changed over time and helped me figure out my goals in life, not limited by my career alone.</p> 

      <p>
        During the Summers just after the First Year, I was constantly looking out for options available to an undergraduate after completing the degree at IITK. The best source for me turned out to be my seniors. I used to reach out to them and ask them about their internship and placement experiences and what all roles were open etc.
      </p>

      <p>
        The same summer, I got an opportunity to work for the IITK Summer of Code, where after three months of engineering and development, my team of 5 people won the 1st Prize! This was my first exposure to Software Engineering, and I found that this was one of the fields where I was not getting bored, and I was being creative throughout the development cycle.
      </p>

      <p>
        Later on, I decided to explore the Data Science field as well though an academic project under Prof. Pranamesh Chakraborty. I even worked as a Product Analyst in a startup GreenCure founded by IITK alumni. And I did my summer internship at LTI - Larsen & Toubro Infotech.
      </p>

      <p>
        Although I was doing quite well in all these domains, LTI even offered me a PPO! But through all these experiences, I figured out a field where I was naturally interested and creative in a flow. I remember, during the Summer of Code and LTI Intern, I was doing my best, and I was not feeling any sort of significant pain, frustration or boredom even when I was working till 4 AM.
      </p>

      <p>
        These were some of the major signals to me regarding what should I choose as a career option, and I started reading and interacting more and more with seniors and professionals from the Software Engineering domain, which further aligned my career goals, and I finally decided to prepare for the Software Engineering roles for the placements.
      </p>

      <p>
        <b> Some Key Decisions! </b>
      </p>

      <img class="img2" src="/img/Student-section/placement-postulates/blogs/Yashvardhan-Raizada/2.jpg">

      <p>
        I would like to emphasize here that campus placements are one of the easiest ways a UG can try to choose a career path of his/her choice. So I would say, spend some time exploring yourself
and your future aspirations and decide on not more than 2-3 job profiles which you will be aiming for. And out of those, your top preference should have 70-80% approval from your side; the rest should be back up! This will help you not only do a much-focused preparation but will really help you get into the best companies in your desired job role.
      </p>

      <p>
        And when you think along these lines and interact more and more with your seniors, you will get to know not only the career aspect but many aspects of life where you will have to make similar types of choices, and you will get more and more clear about why you would like to chose a particular job role R at a company C, and how it would be helpful in your future!
      </p>

      <img class="img1" src="/img/Student-section/placement-postulates/blogs/Yashvardhan-Raizada/3.jpg">
      <p>
       <b> Placement Preparation </b>
      </p>
      
      <p>
        A lot of articles can be found. My preparation was mainly through LeetCode, InterviewBit, and Brainstellar. I had made up my mind to target SDE/ML and Quant/Analytics roles.
      </p>

      <p>
        InterviewBit is a great resource. I went through the tutorials on DS/Algo, articles on ML, and other CS Fundamental topics: OOP, CN, DBMS, and OS. Try to practice 2-3 questions from each basket.
      </p>

      <p>
        I also learned SQL and practiced writing queries here. Also, one can go through some of the system design questions as well to get to know more about real-world software engineering. It may help you in some of the advanced technical rounds of some startups.
      </p>

      <p>
        Besides these, I regularly attempted Weekly and Bi-Weekly contests on LeetCode, apart from solving mock assessments on LC and practicing mock interviews on IB. Be consistent in your practice; it will help you a lot!
      </p>

      <p>
        For puzzles, I practiced questions from the 50 Challenging Problems in Probability, Brainstellar, and InterviewBit puzzles sections. For aptitude, I practiced solving past CAT papers and enrolled in a placement preparation test series by PrepLeaf.
      </p>

      <p>
        But 80% of my time was spent practicing more and more DSA questions and studying ML, CS Fundamental articles on GFG, IB, Medium, etc.
      </p>

      <p>
        Regarding resumes, I would suggest everyone go through the SPO Preparation Folder. Just keep it precise and crisp, not exceeding 1 page. Make sure you are prepared to defend each and every point written on it, even from extracurriculars. Also, do get it reviewed multiple times by at least five seniors till you get satisfied.
      </p>

