      <p>
        <b> The Choice! </b>
      </p>

      <img class="img2" src="/img/Student-section/placement-postulates/blogs/Yashvardhan-Raizada/6.jpg">

      <p>
        Now the choice among the two:
      </p>

      <p>
        Both are pretty good places to launch your career, but one should try to look at least 5-10 years ahead and plan accordingly what one aspires for. As per my research and communication with seniors, I decided to go ahead with Microsoft.
      </p>

      <p>
        The reasons were primarily based on interest and my future career goals. I had three past projects related to the development and data science, and I really enjoyed working on them. Also, I realized that my expertise and original thinking were much more profound in Programming than in Mathematics, although I enjoy both subjects. I had admired the role of a software engineer even before I had joined college, and after a lot of research and first-hand conversations, I really wanted to be a Software Engineer. Hence, I felt just a step closer to my dream job, which I had always wanted.
      </p>

      <p>
        Further looking up at the career trajectory, a Quant at JPMC starts as an analyst and later on progresses to a Quantitative Researcher at mid-levels and then as Vice President. Nature of work is more similar to Data Analyst and Data Scientist, but financial expertise takes over technical at senior positions. Good for people who want to make a career in quantitative finance.
      </p>

      <p>
        In Microsoft, most of us already know a lot about it, its career path, growth, and opportunities. If someone wants to make a career in technology and software, it is one of the best places to launch your career.

      </p>

